		{"id":"6e6961b2af5eace8","x":-520,"y":-640,"width":980,"height":900,"type":"text","text":"# Explain the frontend in natural language\n\nSame style as the backend — how you’d **say it** in the presentation.\n\n---\n\n## 30-second version\n\n> The **frontend** is everything the user **sees and clicks** — ledger pages, the forecast chart, “Connect bank”, and “Ask AI”.\n>\n> I build it with **TypeScript** for safe code, **React** for reusable UI pieces, **Tailwind** and **shadcn** for styling and buttons/cards. **Next.js** ties pages and routes together and can render on the server so the page loads fast. **Node** runs the app locally and on **Vercel**. Finally, the **browser** shows the UI and handles interactive things like Plaid Link and the microphone.\n\n---\n\n## Walk through the slide (top to bottom)\n\n**TypeScript (.ts and .tsx)**  \n> “I write **TypeScript** everywhere. Files ending in **`.tsx`** are UI — pages and components. Plain **`.ts`** files are logic only, like forecast math, with no screen.”\n\n**React — UI library**  \n> “**React** breaks the screen into **components** — a button, a card, the chat box. Each component can hold **state**, like ‘is the user still waiting for an answer?’. When state changes, React updates the screen automatically.”\n\n**Tailwind CSS — styling**  \n> “Instead of big CSS files, I add **utility classes** on each element — colors, spacing, borders. That’s how route badges get teal for LangGraph and violet for the forecast advisor.”\n\n**shadcn/ui — pre-built components**  \n> “**shadcn** gives me ready-made **Button**, **Card**, and **Input** components that already match the design. I don’t rebuild a button from scratch every time.”\n\n**Next.js — routing, API, SSR, build**  \n> “**Next.js** is the framework on top of React. Each URL like `/ledger` or `/simulation` is a **page**. Next.js also hosts my **API routes** on the same project, can **render HTML on the server** for faster first load, and **builds** the production bundle for Vercel.”\n\n**Node.js — dev server, CI, Vercel**  \n> “**Node** is the engine that runs JavaScript outside the browser. Locally, `npm run dev` starts Next.js. In **CI**, Node runs tests and build. On **Vercel**, Node runs the live site when someone visits.”\n\n**Browser — user sees the UI**  \n> “The **browser** is Chrome or Safari on the user’s phone or laptop. It shows the page and runs **client** code — clicks, forms, Plaid popup, voice mic. Sensitive work still goes to the **API** on the server.”\n\n---\n\n## Pages vs components (if they ask)\n\n> “A **page** is a full screen for one URL — like `/balances`. A **component** is a smaller piece reused on many pages — like the Plaid ‘Connect bank’ block or the chat input. Both are usually **`.tsx`** files: TypeScript plus **JSX**, which looks like HTML inside the code.”\n\n---\n\n## Simple analogy\n\n> “**React components** are LEGO bricks. **Tailwind and shadcn** are the colors and standard brick shapes. **Next.js** is the instruction booklet — which page uses which bricks. **The browser** is where the finished model sits in front of the user.”\n\n---\n\n## Tie to your project\n\n> “When someone asks ‘Can we afford a car payment?’, they type in **ForecastSimulator** — that’s frontend. The answer comes back from **`/api/scenario-chat`** — that’s backend. The **route badge** on the result page is frontend too: it shows whether the answer came from deterministic code, LangGraph, documents, or the forecast advisor — so users see **how** the app answered, not just the text.”\n\n---\n\n## Client vs server on the frontend (one sentence)\n\n> “Some UI is built on the **server** first for speed; interactive parts like Plaid and chat run in the **browser** after the page loads.”\n\n---\n\n## If someone asks: “What is JSX?”\n\n> “**JSX** is HTML-like markup inside TypeScript — so I can write `<Button>Connect bank</Button>` instead of complicated JavaScript. That’s why UI files end in **`.tsx`**.”\n\n---\n\n## Frontend vs backend in one breath\n\n> “**Frontend** = what you see and click. **Backend** = API, database, Plaid secrets, AI keys. They’re in the same Next.js project, but the browser only gets safe data back — not passwords.”\n\n---\n\n## Optional slide subtitle\n\n> **Frontend:** TypeScript + React → styled with Tailwind/shadcn → Next.js pages → runs in the browser\n\nSpeak the **30-second version** first, then point at each box only if you have time or someone looks confused."}
